Two Types of Writing Tools

  • WYSIWYG
    • Microsoft Word
    • Google Docs
    • â¦â¦
  • Non-WYSIWYG
    • LaTeX (and variants)
    • Markdown (and variants)
    • Typst

Pros of WYSIWYG Tools

  • You see the âalmost-finalâ product as you write
  • âStandardâ format for submitting manuscripts in many fields
    • Exceptions: Math, Physics, CS
  • Easy to learn/use â no special skills required
  • Fast in many cases
  • Collaborative editing

Cons of WYSIWYG Tools

  • It is hard to write equations (if there are a lot)
  • The current âstandardâ is âLaTeXâ for journals in Math and Physics
  • It may be slow when the document is big (e.g., with a lot of high-quality figures)
  • Compatibility/consistency may be an issue (e.g., format may change from platform to platform)
  • Difficult to number and refer to figures and tables

Pros of LaTeX

  • Standard for journals in Math and Physics
    • If you are a physics Ph.D.Â student, you should learn the basics of LaTeX.
  • Great for dealing with equations and math notations
  • Separation of content and style
  • Auto-numbering and referring to figures and tables
  • Plain text and thus consistent from platform to platform

Cons of LaTeX

  • Typically do not see what you get when you write
  • Fairly steep learning curve
  • Collaborators unfamiliar with LaTeX will have difficulty reviewing your manuscripts
  • Difficult to master high-level functions

Combination: Markdown + Pandoc

  • Markdown: a simplified version of LaTeX
  • Pandoc: a universal document converter

Quarto - a tool-chain for Markdown+Pandoc

Additional features/advantages of Quarto

  • Easy to include and run Python code (and other code)

  • Easy to convert among different formats

    • high-quality articles, reports, presentations, websites, blogs, and books in HTML, PDF, MS Word, ePub, and more.

Workflow 1 for Writing in WANGLAB

  • If your manuscript will have more than 10 symbols and equations

    1. Write your manuscript in Markdown (Quarto)
      • VS Code + Quarto Extension
      • RStudio
    2. Export as PDF for reviewing and submission

      • Export to LaTeX for tweaking if needed

      • Export to Word for collaboratorsâ reviewing if needed

Preferred Workflow in WangLab: Markdown (Quarto)

  • Cross-platform (Windows, Mac, Linux, iPad)
  • Plain-text (consistency between different versions)
  • Can easily convert to any format
  • Reproductive research (easy to include and run code)
  • Easy to label and reference figures
  • Easy to include equations and math
